properties.description:
* WHAT...One to two feet of inundation above ground level
expected in low-lying areas near shorelines and tidal
waterways.

* WHERE...Salem and Cumberland.

* WHEN...From 11 PM Sunday to 5 AM EST Monday.

* IMPACTS...At this level, flooding begins on the most
vulnerable roads in coastal and bayside communities, and along
inland tidal waterways. Some partial or full road closures are
possible. At this level, widespread roadway flooding occurs
along tidal waterways. Some roads become impassable. Minor
damage to vulnerable structures may begin to occur.
properties.instruction:
If travel is required, allow extra time as some roads may be
closed. Do not drive around barricades or through water of
unknown depth. Take the necessary actions to protect flood-prone
property.

properties.areaDesc: Coastal Volusia; Coastal Indian River; Coastal St. Lucie; Coastal Martin; Mainland Northern Brevard; Northern Brevard Barrier Islands; Mainland Southern Brevard; Southern Brevard Barrier Islands
properties.headline: Rip Current Statement issued December 16 at 1:55PM EST until December 18 at 4:00AM EST by NWS Melbourne FL
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the Coastal Flood Advisory, minor coastal flooding.
For the High Surf Advisory, large breaking waves of 6 to 12
feet in the surf zone. For the High Rip Current Risk, dangerous
rip currents.

* WHERE...Coastal Volusia, Coastal Indian River, Coastal Saint
Lucie, Coastal Martin, Mainland Northern Brevard, Northern
Brevard Barrier Islands, Mainland Southern Brevard and
Southern Brevard Barrier Islands Counties.

* WHEN...For the Coastal Flood Advisory, until 4 AM EST Sunday.
For the High Surf Advisory, until 4 AM EST Sunday. For the High
Rip Current Risk, through late Sunday night.

* IMPACTS...Some flooding of low-lying lots, parks and roadways
may occur near the shoreline. Dangerous swimming and surfing
conditions and localized beach erosion. Rip currents can sweep
even the best swimmers away from shore into deeper water.
properties.instruction:
Onshore winds and above normal tides will combine to generate
flooding of low areas along the shore. Do not drive around
barricades or through water of unknown depth. Take the necessary
actions to protect flood-prone property.

High surf will affect the beaches in the advisory area, producing
localized beach erosion and dangerous swimming conditions.
Swimmers should remain out of the water due to large breaking
waves and dangerous surf conditions.

Rip currents are powerful channels of water flowing quickly away
from shore, which occur most often at low spots or breaks in the
sandbar and in the vicinity of structures such as jetties and
piers. Heed the advice of lifeguards, beach patrol flags and
signs.

properties.areaDesc: Lower Treasure Valley; Upper Weiser River; Oregon Lower Treasure Valley
properties.headline: Dense Fog Advisory issued December 16 at 11:50AM MST until December 16 at 1:00PM MST by NWS Boise ID
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the Dense Fog Advisory, visibility one quarter mile
ore less in dense fog. For the Air Stagnation Advisory, an
extended period of stagnant air, with light winds and little
vertical mixing.

* WHERE...In Idaho, Lower Treasure Valley ID and Upper Weiser
River. In Oregon, Oregon Lower Treasure Valley.

* WHEN...For the Dense Fog Advisory, until 1 PM MST this
afternoon. For the Air Stagnation Advisory, until 11 PM MST
Monday.

* IMPACTS...Hazardous driving conditions due to low visibility.
Periods of air stagnation can lead to the buildup of
pollutants near the surface.
properties.instruction:
If driving, slow down, use your headlights, and leave plenty of
distance ahead of you.

An Air Stagnation Advisory concerns itself with meteorological
conditions only. For more information on air pollution in Idaho,
visit website www.deq.idaho.gov. For Oregon, visit website
www.oregon.gov/deq.

If possible, reduce or eliminate activities that contribute to
air pollution, such as outdoor burning, and the use of
residential wood burning devices.  Reduce vehicle trips and
vehicle idling as much as possible.

possible.

* WHERE...Portions of Florida, including the following areas, Baker,
Bradford, Central Marion, Coastal Duval, Coastal Flagler, Coastal
Nassau, Coastal St. Johns, Eastern Alachua, Eastern Clay, Eastern

higher amounts possible. Combined with the threat of coastal

properties.headline: Flood Watch issued December 16 at 1:32PM EST until December 18 at 6:00AM EST by NWS Baltimore MD/Washington DC
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall is possible.

* WHERE...Portions of DC, including the following , District of
Columbia, Maryland, including the following areas, Anne Arundel,
Calvert, Carroll, Cecil, Central and Southeast Howard, Central and
Southeast Montgomery, Charles, Northern Baltimore, Northwest
Harford, Northwest Howard, Northwest Montgomery, Prince Georges,
Southeast Harford, Southern Baltimore and St. Marys, and Virginia,
including the following areas, Arlington/Falls Church/Alexandria,
Central and Southeast Prince William/Manassas/Manassas Park,
Eastern Loudoun, Fairfax, King George, Northwest Prince William,
Spotsylvania and Stafford.

* WHEN...From Sunday evening through early Monday morning

* IMPACTS...Excessive runoff may result in flooding of rivers,
creeks, streams, and other low-lying and flood-prone locations.
Flooding may occur in poor drainage and urban areas. Storm drains
and ditches may become clogged with debris.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- One to three inches of rain are mostly likely Sunday evening
through early Monday morning. This amount of rain could cause
flooding of small streams, creeks and urban areas. Localized
amounts up to four inches are possible along and east of
I-95.
- Please visit www.weather.gov/safety/flood for flood safety
and preparedness information
properties.instruction:
You should monitor later forecasts and be alert for possible Flood
Warnings. Those living in areas prone to flooding should be prepared
to take action should flooding develop.

properties.areaDesc: South  Willamette Valley
properties.headline: Air Stagnation Advisory issued December 16 at 9:58AM PST until December 18 at 4:00AM PST by NWS Portland OR
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the Dense Fog Advisory, visibility one quarter mile
or less in dense fog. For the Air Stagnation Advisory, a
period of stagnant air with light winds is expected.

* WHERE...South Willamette Valley.

* WHEN...For the Dense Fog Advisory, until 1 PM PST this
afternoon. For the Air Stagnation Advisory, until 4 AM PST
Monday.

* IMPACTS...Hazardous driving conditions due to low visibility.
Air stagnation could result in the development and persistence
of poor air quality.
properties.instruction:
If driving, slow down, use your headlights, and leave plenty of
distance ahead of you.

People with respiratory illness should follow their physician's
advice for dealing with high levels of air pollution during
periods of stagnant air.

State air quality agencies highly recommend that no outdoor
burning occur and that residential wood burning devices be
limited as much as possible. According to state air quality
agencies, prolonged periods of stagnant air can hold pollutants
close to the ground where people live and breathe. Check with
your local burn agency for any current restrictions in your area.

properties.headline: Dense Fog Advisory issued December 16 at 9:25AM PST until December 16 at 12:00PM PST by NWS Spokane WA
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the Dense Fog Advisory, visibility less than one mile
in dense fog. For the Air Stagnation Advisory, stagnant conditions
will have potential to trap pollutants near the ground with
deteriorated air quality.

* WHERE...Coeur d'Alene, Hayden, Post Falls, Worley, Athol,
Eastport, Bonners Ferry, Schweitzer Mountain Road, Priest River,
Clark Fork, and Sandpoint.

* WHEN...For the Dense Fog Advisory, until noon PST today. For the
Air Stagnation Advisory, until 10 AM PST Monday.

* IMPACTS...Low visibility could make driving conditions hazardous.
Periods of air stagnation can lead to the buildup of pollutants
near the surface.
properties.instruction:
If driving, slow down, use your headlights, and leave plenty of
distance ahead of you.

Buildup of fine pollution particles can be harmful to those
sensitive to air pollution including people with lung and heart
problems, people with diabetes, children and the elderly.

properties.areaDesc: Aransas Islands; Kleberg Islands; Nueces Islands; Calhoun Islands
properties.headline: Coastal Flood Advisory issued December 16 at 11:22AM CST until December 17 at 6:00AM CST by NWS Corpus Christi TX
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the High Rip Current Risk, dangerous rip currents.
For the Coastal Flood Advisory, minor coastal flooding
expected.

* WHERE...Aransas Islands, Kleberg Islands, Nueces Islands and
Calhoun Islands Counties.

* WHEN...For the High Rip Current Risk, through Sunday
afternoon. For the Coastal Flood Advisory, from 3 PM this
afternoon to 6 AM CST Sunday.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of lots, parks, and roads with only
isolated road closures expected. Rip currents can sweep even
the most experienced swimmers away from shore into deeper
water. These rip currents can become life-threatening to
anyone entering the surf.
properties.instruction:
If travel is required, allow extra time as some roads may be
closed. Do not drive around barricades or through water of
unknown depth. Take the necessary actions to protect flood-prone
property.

Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

properties.headline: Flood Watch issued December 16 at 11:43AM EST until December 17 at 7:00AM EST by NWS Key West FL
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall continues to be
possible.

* WHERE...All of the Florida Keys, in Monroe County.

* WHEN...Through Sunday morning.

* IMPACTS...Excessive runoff may result in flooding of low-lying and
flood-prone locations. Flooding may occur in poor drainage and
urban areas. Storm drains and ditches may become clogged with
debris. The heavy rainfall may occur during the times of the early
morning high tides, which would exacerbate drainage concerns.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- Strong to severe thunderstorms remain possible across the
Florida Keys this afternoon and overnight. Rainfall rates
could exceed 2 inches per hour within the strongest storms.
Rainfall totals over the next 18-hours will range from 2 to 4
inches, with localized amounts around 5 inches.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
You should monitor later forecasts and be alert for possible Flood
Statements or Advisories. Those living in areas prone to flooding
should be prepared to take action should flooding develop.

properties.description:

to 11 feet expected in the surf zone. For the Coastal Flood

waterways.

erosion.

average tide conditions. Additional locations may experience
flooding during periods of heavy rainfall, high winds, or
other factors.

unknown depth. Take the necessary actions to protect flood-prone
property.

dangerous surf conditions.

properties.description:
* WHAT...Southeast winds 20 to 25 mph, with frequent gusts near 40
mph.

* WHERE...Florida Keys.

* WHEN...Until 11 PM EST this evening.

* IMPACTS...A Wind Advisory means that sustained winds of 30 to 39
mph, or frequent gusts in excess of 35 mph are expected. Winds
this strong can make driving difficult, especially for high
profile vehicles. Wind gusts along the Overseas Highway will be
highest on bridges and overpasses.
properties.instruction:

furniture, holiday decorations, and other loose or lightweight
outdoor objects.

properties.description:
* WHAT...Water levels are running about 1 to 1.5 feet above the
predicted tides this morning, and the combination of strong
onshore winds will result in the potential for moderate
saltwater flooding. Peak water levels during the early morning
high tides will reach around 1.5 feet above mean higher high
water.

* WHERE...Middle and Lower Florida Keys.

* WHEN...Through Sunday morning.

* IMPACTS...Saltwater flooding of low elevation streets and lots
is expected. Flooding will be exacerbated by bouts of heavy
rainfall. Some storm drains will overflow, and some seawalls
and docks will be overtopped. Boaters can expect less clearance
under fixed bridges. Motorists should remember that persistent
puddles around the times of high tide are almost certain to
contain a mix of saltwater.
properties.instruction:

closed. Do not drive around barricades or through water of
unknown depth. Take the necessary actions to protect flood-prone
property.

properties.headline: Flood Watch issued December 16 at 10:45AM EST until December 17 at 7:00AM EST by NWS Miami FL
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall continues to be
possible.

* WHERE...A portion of southeast Florida, including the following
areas, Coastal Broward County, Coastal Miami Dade County, Coastal
Palm Beach County, Far South Miami-Dade County, Inland Miami-Dade
County, Metro Broward County, Metro Palm Beach County and
Metropolitan Miami Dade.

* WHEN...Through Sunday morning.

* IMPACTS...Excessive runoff may result in flooding of rivers,
creeks, streams, and other low-lying and flood-prone locations.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- Widespread showers and thunderstorms are expected to develop
late this afternoon through early Sunday morning as low
pressure develops over the Gulf of Mexico and moves northeast
across northern Florida. Total rainfall amounts of 3 to 6
inches are possible over the eastern areas of South Florida
through early Sunday morning with higher amounts where any
showers and thunderstorms train over the same area. This
amount of rainfall may lead to some flooding issues over the
east coast metro of South Florida due to the grounds being
already saturated from previous rainfall this week.

properties.headline: Air Stagnation Advisory issued December 16 at 8:40AM MST until December 18 at 11:00PM MST by NWS Missoula MT
properties.description:
* WHAT...Stagnation conditions will trap pollutants, leading to
deteriorating air quality.

* WHERE...Flathead/Mission Valleys, Kootenai/Cabinet Region, West
Glacier Region, Bitterroot/Sapphire Mountains, Lower Clark Fork
Region, and Potomac/Seeley Lake Region.

* WHEN...Until 11 PM MST Monday.

* IMPACTS...Periods of air stagnation can lead to the build up of
pollutants near the surface.
properties.instruction:
Persons with respiratory illness should follow their physicians
advice for dealing with high levels of air pollution during periods
of stagnant air.

According to state air quality agencies, prolonged period of
stagnant air can hold pollutants close to the ground where people
live and breathe. Check with your local burn agency for any current
restrictions in your area.

properties.headline: High Surf Advisory issued December 16 at 10:31AM EST until December 17 at 7:00AM EST by NWS Miami FL
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the High Surf Advisory, large breaking waves of 9 to
12 feet in the surf zone. For the High Rip Current Risk,
dangerous rip currents. For the Coastal Flood Statement,
isolated minor coastal flooding expected.

* WHERE...Coastal Palm Beach County, Coastal Broward County and
Coastal Miami Dade County.

* WHEN...For the High Rip Current Risk, through late Sunday
night. For the High Surf Advisory, until 7 AM EST Sunday. For
the Coastal Flood Statement, until 1 PM EST this afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Some water on low lying roads and property. Dangerous
swimming and surfing conditions and localized beach erosion. Rip
currents can sweep even the best swimmers away from shore into
deeper water.
properties.instruction:
Do not drive through flooded roadways.

Inexperienced swimmers should remain out of the water due to
dangerous surf conditions.

Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

properties.areaDesc: Matanuska Valley
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued December 16 at 6:00AM AKST by NWS Anchorage AK
properties.description:
Northeasterly winds will develop late this morning across the
Matanuska Valley and increase through this afternoon. Gusts to 35
mph are possible, resulting in localized areas of blowing and
drifting snow.

Winds will then quickly diminish and shift to the southwest as a
frontal system moves through. The shift in winds will also allow
snow to develop across the Matanuska Valley. 2 to 4 inches of
snow, with locally higher amounts, are possible Saturday night
through early Sunday morning.

NWSheadline: GUSTY WINDS WITH AREAS OF DRIFTING AND BLOWING SNOW LIKELY FOR THE MATANUSKA VALLEY SATURDAY AFTERNOON THEN WIDESPREAD SNOW SATURDAY NIGHT

properties.areaDesc: Anchorage
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued December 16 at 6:00AM AKST by NWS Anchorage AK
properties.description:
Southeasterly winds will develop this morning along Turnagain Arm
and across the Anchorage Hillside and increase through this
afternoon. These winds will peak in intensity this evening with
sustained winds of 30 to 45 mph and gusts to 65 mph. The
strongest wind gusts are expected on the Anchorage Hillside.
Localized areas of blowing snow are likely with these gusty winds.

Winds will then quickly diminish and shift to the southwest as a
frontal system moves through. The shift in winds will also allow
snow to develop across the Anchorage Bowl. 2 to 4 inches of snow,
with locally higher amounts, are possible Saturday night through
early Sunday morning. Southerly wind gusts to 25 mph may cause
localized areas of blowing and drifting snow across the Anchorage
Bowl Sunday.

NWSheadline: STRONG WIND GUSTS AND AREAS OF BLOWING SNOW LIKELY FOR THE ANCHORAGE HILLSIDE THROUGH SATURDAY EVENING. WIDESPREAD SNOW FOR THE ANCHORAGE BOWL SATURDAY NIGHT

properties.areaDesc: Western Prince William Sound
properties.headline: Winter Storm Warning issued December 16 at 5:38AM AKST until December 17 at 3:00AM AKST by NWS Anchorage AK
properties.description:
AAA

* WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 6 to 12
inches. Winds gusting as high as 40 mph near Whittier and 30
mph through Turnagain Pass.

* WHERE...Whittier and Turnagain Pass to Summit Lake.

* WHEN...From 11 AM this morning to 3 AM AKST Sunday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on hazardous travel conditions.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Light snow and gusty winds will develop
by late Saturday morning. The snow will become heavier
throughout the afternoon, reaching rates of 1 to 2 inches per
hour between 4 pm and 10 pm. The combination of heavy snow and
gusty winds will significantly reduce visibility. Temperatures
will warm into the mid 30s with this event. As such, blowing
snow should not be a concern during periods of heavier snow
this afternoon and evening. Rain may mix with snow around
Whittier at times. Any rain will help lower overall snow
amounts. The snow is expected to taper off Sunday morning.
properties.instruction:
A Winter Storm Warning for snow means severe winter weather
conditions will make travel very hazardous. If you must travel,
keep an extra flashlight, food and water in your vehicle in case
of an emergency.

For the latest road conditions call 5 1 1 or visit
511.alaska.gov.

NWSheadline: WINTER STORM WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT FROM 1 PM THIS AFTERNOON TO 3 AM AKST SUNDAY

511.alaska.gov.

properties.areaDesc: Bristol Bay
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued December 16 at 4:46AM AKST by NWS Anchorage AK
properties.description:
Gale force south to southwesterly winds will increase through
Saturday evening as a strong storm system moves from the eastern
Bering to Bristol Bay. The strong winds will result in elevated
water levels with the potential for water pushing up through
cracks in the ice and ice pushing up on shore along south and west
facing shorelines. The greatest chance for elevated water levels
and potential ice shoves is expected to be along the Northern
Bristol Bay coast between Togiak and Naknek.

Water levels are expected to rise above normal highest tide
by early Saturday afternoon with the highest water levels
expected Saturday evening before slowly subsiding late Saturday
night. residents with interests along the coast should move items
well above the normal high tide line.

properties.headline: Air Stagnation Advisory issued December 16 at 5:42AM PST until December 18 at 10:00AM PST by NWS Medford OR
properties.description:
* WHAT...Stagnant air is expected, which may lead to
deteriorating air quality.

* WHERE...Valleys of southern Oregon and northern California.

* WHEN...Until 10 AM PST Monday.

* IMPACTS...Air stagnation is likely to result in diminishing
air quality with time, especially in and near areas with
significant sources of air pollution. Diminished air quality
is likely to cause health issues for people with respiratory
problems if precautions are not taken.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/map/?wfo=mfr
properties.instruction:
People with respiratory illness should follow their physician's
advice for dealing with diminished air quality. N95 masks are
effective at filtering out the majority of harmful air
particulates.

State air quality agencies highly recommend that no outdoor
burning occur and that residential wood burning devices be
limited as much as possible. According to state air quality
agencies, prolonged periods of stagnant air can hold pollutants
close to the ground where people live and breathe. Check with
your local burn agency for any current restrictions in your area.

properties.areaDesc: San Juan and Vicinity; Northeast; North Central; Northwest
properties.headline: High Surf Advisory issued December 16 at 9:30AM AST until December 16 at 6:00PM AST by NWS San Juan PR
properties.description:
* WHAT...Life-threatening rip currents due to rough surf and
large breaking waves between 8 and 11 feet and locally higher
at times.

* WHERE...Beaches from Aguadilla eastward to Fajardo across
northern Puerto Rico.

* WHEN...For the High Surf Advisory, until 6 PM AST Saturday.
For the High Rip Current Risk, through late Sunday night.

* IMPACTS...Dangerous swimming conditions and localized beach
erosion. Rip currents that can sweep even the best swimmers
away from shore into deeper water where it becomes difficult
to return to safety.
properties.instruction:
There is a high risk of rip currents.

Rip currents are powerful channels of water flowing quickly away
from shore, which occur most often at low spots or breaks in the
sandbar and in the vicinity of structures such as groins, jetties
and piers. Heed the advice of lifeguards, beach patrol flags and
signs.

If you become caught in a rip current, yell for help. Remain
calm, do not exhaust yourself and stay afloat while waiting for
help. If you have to swim out of a rip current, swim parallel to
shore and back toward the beach when possible. Do not attempt to
swim directly against a rip current as you will tire quickly.

A High Surf Advisory means that high surf will affect beaches in
the advisory area, producing localized beach erosion and
dangerous swimming conditions.

properties.areaDesc: Pinellas; Coastal Hillsborough; Coastal Manatee
properties.headline: Rip Current Statement issued December 16 at 7:40AM EST until December 18 at 7:00AM EST by NWS Tampa Bay Ruskin FL
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the Coastal Flood Advisory, minor coastal flooding
expected. For the High Surf Advisory, large breaking waves of 6
feet. For the High Rip Current Risk, dangerous rip currents
expected.

* WHERE...Pinellas, Coastal Hillsborough and Coastal Manatee
Counties.

* WHEN...For the Coastal Flood Advisory, from 7 PM this evening
to 7 AM EST Sunday. For the High Surf Advisory, from 1 AM
Sunday to 7 AM EST Monday. For the High Rip Current Risk, from
late tonight through Monday morning.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of lots, parks, and roads with only
isolated road closures expected. Dangerous swimming and
surfing conditions and localized beach erosion. Rip currents
can sweep even the best swimmers away from shore into deeper
water.
properties.instruction:
If travel is required, allow extra time as some roads may be
closed. Do not drive around barricades or through water of
unknown depth. Take the necessary actions to protect flood-prone
property.

Inexperienced swimmers should remain out of the water due to
dangerous surf conditions.

Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

NWSheadline: COASTAL FLOOD ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM 7 PM THIS EVENING TO 7 AM EST SUNDAY... ...HIGH SURF ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM 1 AM SUNDAY TO 7 AM EST MONDAY... ...HIGH RIP CURRENT RISK IN EFFECT FROM LATE TONIGHT THROUGH MONDAY MORNING

Counties.

direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

properties.description:

25 kt with gusts up to 35 kt and seas 7 to 10 ft. For the Small
Craft Advisory, winds becoming more northerly 20 kt with gusts
up to 30 kt and seas 6 to 8 ft expected.

vessel for severe conditions.

NWSheadline: WIND ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT FROM 5 PM THIS AFTERNOON TO 10 AM EST SUNDAY

properties.areaDesc: Cocke Smoky Mountains; Southeast Greene; Blount Smoky Mountains; Sevier Smoky Mountains
properties.headline: High Wind Warning issued December 16 at 4:27AM EST until December 17 at 10:00AM EST by NWS Morristown TN
properties.description:
* WHAT...Southeast winds 30 to 40 mph with gusts up to 60 mph
expected.

* WHERE...Cocke Smoky Mountains, Southeast Greene, Blount Smoky
Mountains and Sevier Smoky Mountains Counties.

* WHEN...From 5 PM this afternoon to 10 AM EST Sunday.

* IMPACTS...Damaging winds will blow down trees and power lines.
Widespread power outages are expected. Travel will be
difficult, especially for high profile vehicles.
properties.instruction:
People should avoid being outside in forested areas and around
trees and branches. If possible, remain in the lower levels of
your home during the windstorm, and avoid windows. Use caution if
you must drive.

NWSheadline: HIGH WIND WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT FROM 5 PM THIS AFTERNOON TO 10 AM EST SUNDAY

properties.areaDesc: Northern Outer Banks
properties.headline: High Surf Advisory issued December 16 at 4:17AM EST until December 18 at 7:00PM EST by NWS Newport/Morehead City NC
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the High Surf Advisory, large breaking waves of 8 to
14 feet expected in the surf zone. For the Coastal Flood Watch,
2 to 4 feet of inundation above ground level possible in low-
lying areas near shorelines and tidal waterways.

* WHERE...Northern Outer Banks.

* WHEN...For the High Surf Advisory, from 4 PM Sunday to 7 PM
EST Monday. For the Coastal Flood Watch, from Sunday afternoon
through Monday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Up to 2 to 4 feet of inundation above ground level is
possible in low-lying areas near shorelines and tidal waterways
resulting in a low threat of property damage. Some roads and low
lying property including parking lots, parks, lawns, and homes
adjacent to the waterfront will experience shallow flooding.
Some shoreline erosion will occur. Dangerous swimming and
surfing conditions and localized beach erosion.
properties.instruction:
If travel is required, allow extra time as some roads may be
closed. Do not drive around barricades or through water of
unknown depth. Take the necessary actions to protect flood-prone
property.

Inexperienced swimmers should remain out of the water due to
dangerous surf conditions.

properties.areaDesc: Majuro
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued December 16 at 6:14PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
properties.description:
The Joint Typhoon Warning Center's Invest 92W is centered near
4N172E, or 150 miles south of Majuro. 92W is still loosely organized
per analysis of satellite and other available tools. The invest is
currently rated LOW, meaning tropical cyclone develop is not expected
in the next 24 hours. Model guidance moves 92W north-northeast over
the next 24 hours with some models hinting at some strengthening as
the system approaches Majuro from the south. Expect periods of heavy
rainfall and gusts to 30 knots, with occasional gusts up to 35 knots
possible, Sunday and Sunday night. Models vary on the solution,
though the consensus is for 92W to strengthen south of Majuro, then
weaken and either move off to the east or dissipate.

Residents should monitor local weather forecasts and conditions
closely over the next 24 to 48 hours as 92W remains in the vicinity.
Stay up to date with information from your Weather Service office in
Majuro, and for information from the local emergency management
office. The latest Majuro forecast can be found at
weather.gov/gum/PublicForecasts.

properties.headline: Flood Watch issued December 16 at 3:11AM EST until December 18 at 6:00PM EST by NWS Mount Holly NJ
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall continues to be
possible.

* WHERE...Portions of Delaware, including the following areas,
Delaware Beaches, Inland Sussex, Kent, and New Castle. Portions of
northeast Maryland, including the following areas, Caroline, Kent
MD, Queen Annes, and Talbot. Portions of New Jersey, including the
following areas, Atlantic, Atlantic Coastal Cape May, Camden, Cape
May, Coastal Atlantic, Coastal Ocean, Cumberland, Eastern
Monmouth, Gloucester, Hunterdon, Mercer, Middlesex, Morris,
Northwestern Burlington, Ocean, Salem, Somerset, Southeastern

Pennsylvania, including the following areas, Berks, Carbon,
Delaware, Eastern Chester, Eastern Montgomery, Lehigh, Lower
Bucks, Monroe, Northampton, Philadelphia, Upper Bucks, Western
Chester, and Western Montgomery.

* WHEN...From Sunday evening through Monday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Excessive runoff may result in flooding of rivers,
creeks, streams, and other low-lying and flood-prone locations.
Flooding may occur in poor drainage and urban areas.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- Rainfall totals of 1.5 to 3.0 inches are forecast across the
watch area Sunday into Monday, with the heaviest falling
overnight Sunday night. The ground is more saturated due to
heavier rain over the last couple of weeks. A period of
higher hourly rainfall rates will be possible later Sunday
night into early Monday morning, and this can locally enhance
the flooding especially in some urban areas.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
You should monitor later forecasts and be alert for possible Flood
Warnings. Those living in areas prone to flooding should be prepared
to take action should flooding develop.

moderate coastal flooding. This could result in flooding of
roadways near the coast and water could potentially surround
structures immediately along the coastline.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...The Coastal Flood Watch may be discontinued
later today should future forecasts show the storm system moving
further south and east of Dixie County further decreasing the
coastal flood threat.
properties.instruction:
If travel is required, allow extra time as some roads may be
closed. Do not drive around barricades or through water of
unknown depth. Take the necessary actions to protect flood-prone
property.

* WHERE...St Johns River Basin.

* WHEN...Until 10 AM EST Sunday.

NWSheadline: COASTAL FLOOD ADVISORY NOW IN EFFECT UNTIL 10 AM EST SUNDAY

properties.areaDesc: Coastal Nassau; Coastal Duval; Coastal St. Johns; Coastal Flagler; Coastal Glynn; Coastal Camden
properties.headline: Coastal Flood Advisory issued December 16 at 2:43AM EST until December 17 at 10:00AM EST by NWS Jacksonville FL
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the Coastal Flood Advisory, minor coastal flooding.
For the High Surf Advisory, large breaking waves of 6 to 10
feet. For the High Rip Current Risk, dangerous rip currents.

* WHERE...Southeast Georgia and Northeast Florida Beaches.

* WHEN...For the Coastal Flood Advisory, until 10 AM EST Sunday.
For the High Rip Current Risk, through Sunday morning.

* IMPACTS...Flooding of lots, parks, and roads with only
isolated road closures expected. Dangerous swimming and
surfing conditions and localized beach erosion. Rip currents
can sweep even the best swimmers away from shore into deeper
water.
properties.instruction:
If travel is required, allow extra time as some roads may be
closed. Do not drive around barricades or through water of
unknown depth. Take the necessary actions to protect flood-prone
property.

Remain out of the water due to dangerous surf conditions.

If caught in a rip current, relax and float. Don't swim against
the current. If able, swim in a direction following the
shoreline. If unable to escape, face the shore and call or wave
for help.

properties.headline: Wind Advisory issued December 16 at 2:33AM EST until December 17 at 1:00PM EST by NWS Tallahassee FL
properties.description:
* WHAT...Northeast winds 15 to 25 mph with gusts of 30 to 40 mph
expected on top of saturated soils.

* WHERE...Portions of the Big Bend of Florida and south central
Georgia.

* WHEN...From 7 PM this evening to 1 PM EST Sunday.

* IMPACTS...Gusty winds could blow around unsecured objects. Tree
limbs and weak trees could be blown down and a few power
outages may result.

profile vehicle. Secure outdoor objects.

properties.areaDesc: Inland Jefferson; Madison; Inland Taylor; Lafayette; Coastal Jefferson; Coastal Taylor; Colquitt; Cook; Berrien; Thomas; Brooks; Lowndes; Lanier
properties.headline: Flood Watch issued December 16 at 2:22AM EST until December 17 at 10:00AM EST by NWS Tallahassee FL
properties.description:
* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall is possible.

* WHERE...Portions of the Big Bend of Florida, including the
following areas, Coastal Jefferson, Coastal Taylor, Inland
Jefferson, Inland Taylor, Lafayette and Madison and south central
Georgia, including the following areas, Berrien, Brooks, Colquitt,
Cook, Lanier, Lowndes and Thomas.

* WHEN...From this evening through Sunday morning.

* IMPACTS...Excessive runoff may result in flooding of rivers,
creeks, streams, and other low-lying and flood-prone locations.
Flooding may occur in poor drainage and urban areas.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- Rainfall totals of 2 to 4 inches with locally higher amounts
are expected through Sunday morning. With the ground
saturated from previous rainfall, flooding is possible.
- http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
properties.instruction:
You should monitor later forecasts and be alert for possible Flood
Warnings. Those living in areas prone to flooding should be prepared
to take action should flooding develop.
